<BaseLayout title="Starting dialysis: what to expect" description="Your first dialysis sessions at St. John Biocare, step by step, with the fear taken out.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Starting dialysis: what to expect</h1>
      <p class="lead">The unknown is the scariest part. Here's what actually happens.</p>

      <h2>Before your first session</h2>
      <p>We review your records, check your access, and explain the plan and the costs. You'll meet the nurse and doctor who'll care for you. Nothing begins until you understand it.</p>

      <h2>During a session</h2>
      <p>You'll sit in a comfortable chair while the machine gently cleans your blood over a few hours. Many patients rest, read, or watch something. Our nurses monitor you the whole time.</p>

      <h2>Afterwards</h2>
      <p>Most people go home and carry on with their day. Over the first weeks, dialysis becomes a familiar routine rather than an event.</p>

      <div class="notice"><strong>Bring:</strong> a valid ID, your PhilHealth MDR, referral and recent labs, and your medicines list. Wear comfortable clothes.</div>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Request your first visit</a></p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:20px;font-size:.9rem">Medically reviewed by a nephrologist. Last updated: 2026. Educational only; not a substitute for consultation.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
